Tenant Burdens.text: The Tenant shall pay the Landlord, in equal monthly installments, $________________ ("Rent").
If the Premises is sold, the Tenant is to be notified of the new Owner, and if there is a new Manager, their contact details for repairs and maintenance shall be forwarded.
Any other utilities or services not mentioned will be the responsibility of the Tenant.
The Tenant is responsible for all damage that any pet causes, regardless of ownership of said pet and agrees to restore the Premises to its original condition at their expense.
At the end of this Agreement all access provided to the Tenant shall be returned to the Landlord or a fee will be charged to the Tenant or the fee will be subtracted from the Security Deposit.
Failure of the Landlord to deliver possession of the Premises at the start of the Lease Term to the Tenant shall terminate this Agreement at the option of the Tenant.

Furthermore, under such failure to deliver possession by the Landlord, and if the Tenant cancels this Agreement, the Security Deposit (if any) shall be returned to the Tenant along with any other pre-paid rent, fees, including if the Tenant paid a fee during the application process before the execution of this Agreement.
The Tenant shall not be able to sublet the Premises without the written consent from the Landlord.
If the Tenant vacates or abandons the Premises, the Landlord shall immediately have the right to terminate this Agreement.

The Tenant shall, at their own expense and at all times, maintain premises in a clean and sanitary manner, and shall surrender the same at termination hereof, in as good condition as received, normal wear and tear excepted.
Tenant shall not assign this Lease without the prior written consent of the Landlord.
Each individual that is considered a Tenant is jointly and individually liable for all of this Agreement's obligations, including but not limited to rent monies.

The Tenant will be in default if: (a) Tenant does not pay rent or other amounts that are owed; (b) Tenant, their guests, or the Occupant(s) violate this Agreement, rules, or fire, safety, health, or criminal laws, regardless of whether arrest or conviction occurs; (c) Tenant abandons the Premises; (d) Tenant gives incorrect or false information in the rental application; (e) Tenant, or any Occupant(s) is arrested, convicted, or given deferred adjudication for a criminal offense involving actual or potential physical harm to a person, or involving possession, manufacture, or delivery of a controlled substance, marijuana, or drug paraphernalia under state statute; (f) any illegal drugs or paraphernalia are found in the Premises or on the person of the Tenant, guests, or Occupant(s) while on the Premises and/or; (g) as otherwise allowed by law.
MULTIPLE TENANT OR OCCUPANT(S).

If the Tenant possesses any mental or physical impairment, the Landlord shall provide reasonable modifications to the Premises unless the modifications would be too difficult or expensive for the Landlord to provide.
Any impairment(s) of the Tenant are encouraged to be provided and presented to the Landlord in writing in order to seek the most appropriate route for providing the modifications to the Premises.

The Landlord shall not be liable for any damage or injury to the Tenant, or any other person, or to any property, occurring on the Premises, or any part thereof, or in common areas thereof, and the Tenant agrees to hold the Landlord harmless from any claims or damages unless caused solely by the Landlord's negligence.

If said damage was due to the negligence of the Tenant, the Tenant shall be liable to the Landlord for all repairs and for the loss of income due to restoring the Premises back to a livable condition in addition to any other losses that can be proved by the Landlord.
The Landlord and Tenant agree to the terms and conditions and shall be bound until the end of the Lease Term.

Question 1.question: What happens if there are disputes between the landlord and tenant?
Question 1.statement: If any dispute arises during or after the term of the Agreement between the Landlord and Tenant, they shall agree to hold negotiations amongst themselves before any litigation. The Landlord shall not be liable for any damage or injury to the Tenant or any other person occurring on the Premises, except if caused solely by the Landlord's negligence. If the Tenant fails to comply with any of the financial or material provisions of this Agreement, or materially fails to comply with any duties imposed on the Tenant by statute or State laws, within the time period after written notice from the Landlord indicating the intention of the Landlord to terminate the Agreement, the Landlord may terminate the Agreement.

Question 2.question: Who is responsible for what, in terms of maintenance and repair?
Question 2.statement: The Landlord is responsible for repairs to the interior and exterior of the building, and the Tenant is responsible for any damage caused by pets and replacing batteries after initial placement. Any other utilities or services not mentioned are the responsibility of the Tenant. The Tenant must inspect the Premises and write any present damages or needed repairs on a move-in checklist. If said damage was due to the negligence of the Tenant, the Tenant shall be liable to the Landlord for all repairs and for the loss of income due to restoring the Premises back to a livable condition in addition to any other losses that can be proved by the Landlord. The Landlord makes no warranty as to the repair or replacement of any appliances provided. If the Premises is sold, the Tenant is to be notified of the new Owner, and if there is a new Manager, their contact details for repairs and maintenance shall be forwarded. The Landlord does have a manager on the premises that can be contacted for any maintenance or repair.

Question 3.question: What does the lead warning statement say?
Question 3.statement: The lead warning statement requires landlords of pre-1978 housing to disclose the presence of known lead-based paint and/or lead-based paint hazards in the dwelling before renting. Tenants must also receive a federally approved pamphlet on lead poisoning prevention. The presence of lead-based paint and/or lead-based paint hazards must be disclosed, and if there is no knowledge or information on it, a statement must be issued to confirm that. The statement highlights the harmful effects of lead exposure, especially to young children and pregnant women, if not managed properly. Landlords must provide tenants with all available records and reports pertaining to lead-based paint and/or lead-based paint hazards in the housing. If there are known lead-based paint and/or lead-based paint hazards in the housing, they must be explained. It is important for landlords to manage lead-based paint properly to avoid causing health hazards.
